m":"Cranfield, Bedfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Houghton Manor, Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Colchester, Essex, , England":"Colchester, Essex, England"},"en":{"1430–1490":"1430–1490","1421–1495":"1421–1495","1436–Female":"1436–Deceased","1456–1509":"1456–1509","1395–1477":"1395–1477","1399–1451":"1399–1451","1451":"1451","1495":"1495","1395":"1395","1490":"1490","1436":"1436","1456":"1456","1477":"1477","1455":"1455","1399":"1399","1421":"1421","1430":"1430","about 1455":"about 1455","1509":"1509","Bedford, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bedford, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Colchester Castle, Colchester, Essex, England":"Colchester Castle, Colchester, Essex, England","Colchester, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Colchester, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Cranfield, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cranfield, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Houghton Manor, Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Colchester, Essex, , England":"Colchester, Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Sayer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: common occupational name from Middle English <i>sayer</i>, a phonetic variant of   Sawyer  , which in Wales and neighboring English counties may have been reinforced by the synonymous Welsh <i>saer</i> ‘carpenter’ and everywhere by a possible borrowing into Middle English of Old French <i>seieor</i>, <i>saieur</i> ‘sawyer’.","English: rare occupational name perhaps denoting an assayer of metals, or a servant who tasted his lord's food before serving, from Middle English <i>saiour</i> ‘assayer, tester’ (a shortened form of Old French <i>assaiour</i>, ultimately from Late Latin <i>exagium</i>, a derivative of <i>exagmināre</i> ‘to weigh’).","English: rare occupational name for a professional reciter or minstrel, from Middle English <i>seier(e)</i> ‘speaker’."],"variants":[{"name":"Sayre","meanings":["English (Middlesex and Surrey): variant of   Sayer  ."]},{"name":"Sears","meanings":["Irish (Kerry): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Saoghair</b> ‘son of <i>Saoghar</i>’, a borrowing in Anglo-Norman Ireland of the Anglo-Norman French and Middle English personal name <i>Saher</i>, <i>Seier</i> (Old French <i>Seheri</i>), from ancient Germanic <i>Sigeheri</i>, <i>Sighari</i>, composed of the elements <i>sig</i>‘victory’ + <i>hari</i>, <i>heri</i> ‘army’. See   Sayer   5.","English: variant of   Sayers  .","Americanized form of French (or French Canadian)   Cyr   and French <b>Saint-Cyr</b> (see   St. Cyr  ), with the addition of excrescent <i>-s</i>, a common feature of Americanized surnames."]},{"name":"Sear","meanings":["English: variant of   Sayer  .","Americanized form of French (or French Canadian)   Cyr  ."]},{"name":"Searson","meanings":["English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name <i>Saher</i>, <i>Seier</i> (see   Sayer   5) + <i>-son</i>.","English: variant of <b>Searston</b>, a habitational name from Syerston (Nottinghamshire). The placename probably derives from the Old English personal name <i>Sighere</i> (genitive <i>Sigheres</i>) + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’.","Irish (Tipperary): variant of   Sears  ."]},{"name":"Sare","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Sayer  .","English: variant of   Sara  .","Croatian (<b>Šare</b>): nickname derived from <i>šar(en)</i> ‘mottled, gaily colored’, possibly applied to someone with hair of different colors. Compare   Share  ."]},{"name":"Saier","meanings":["South German: occupational name for a farmer, from an agent derivative of Middle High German <i>saien</i> ‘to sow’. Compare   Sayer   8."]},{"name":"Say","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, a habitational name from Sai in Orne or Say in Indre, France, perhaps so called from a Gaulish personal name <i>Saius</i> + the Latin locative suffix <i>-acum</i> (see also French name 3 below).","English: nickname, perhaps for someone who made or sold say, a type of woollen cloth, or for an habitual wearer of clothes made of this material, from Middle English <i>sai(e)</i> ‘say’ (Old French <i>saie</i>, from Latin <i>saga</i>, plural of <i>sagum</i> ‘military cloak’). See also   Sayer  .","French (southern): topographic name from <i>saix</i> (from Latin <i>saxum</i>) ‘rock’, or a habitational name from a place called with this word, for example, Say in Loire, Saix in Tarn and Vienne, Le Saix in Hautes-Alpes, or Les Saix in Isère."]},{"name":"Sayers","meanings":["English: variant of   Sayer  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This name is also established in Ireland.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Saoghair</b>; see   Sears  ."]},{"name":"Sawyer","meanings":["English: occupational name for someone who earned his living by sawing wood, from Middle English <i>sauer(e)</i>, <i>sauw(i)er</i>, also <i>sagh(i)er</i>, <i>sag(i)er</i> ‘sawyer’, a derivative of Old English <i>sagu</i> ‘saw’.","Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) Jewish surname, or translation into English of Jewish   Seger   or some other surname meaning ‘sawyer’, e.g. German   Sager   and Slovenian <b>Žagar</b> (see   Zagar  )."]},{"name":"Seekings","meanings":["English: from the unrecorded Middle English personal name <i>Saykin</i>, a pet form of Middle English and Anglo-Norman French <i>Saher</i>, <i>Seier</i> (see   Sayer   5). The final <i>-s</i> is post-medieval and excrescent."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":25,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Sayer was born in 1430, in Bedfordshire, England, his father, John Sayre II, was 35 and his mother, Vanessa of Poddington, was 31. He married Elizabeth Davidson about 1455, in Colchester, Essex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1490, in Colchester, Essex, England, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1430–1490":"1430–1490","1421–1495":"1421–1495","1436–Female":"1436–Surnud","1456–1509":"1456–1509","1395–1477":"1395–1477","1399–1451":"1399–1451","1451":"1451","1495":"1495","1395":"1395","1490":"1490","1436":"1436","1456":"1456","1477":"1477","1455":"1455","1399":"1399","1421":"1421","1430":"1430","about 1455":"umbes 1455","1509":"1509","Bedford, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bedford, Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Colchester Castle, Colchester, Essex, England":"Colchester Castle, Colchester, Essex, England","Colchester, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Colchester, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cranfield, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cranfield, Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Houghton Manor, Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Colchester, Essex, , England":"Colchester, Essex, England"},"fi":{"1430–1490":"1430–1490","1421–1495":"1421–1495","1436–Female":"1436–Kuollut","1456–1509":"1456–1509","1395–1477":"1395–1477","1399–1451":"1399–1451","1451":"1451","1495":"1495","1395":"1395","1490":"1490","14